</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Although traumatic and iatrogenic bile leaks are rare, they have become more prevalent in recent years due to an increased propensity toward nonsurgical management of patients with liver trauma and an overall increase in the number of hepatobiliary surgeries being performed. Because clinical signs and symptoms of bile leaks are nonspecific and delay in the recognition of bile leaks is associated with high morbidity and mortality rates, imaging is crucial for establishing an early diagnosis and guiding the treatment algorithm. At computed tomography or ultrasonography, free or contained peri- or intrahepatic low-attenuation (low-density) fluid in the setting of recent trauma or hepatobiliary surgery should raise suspicion for a bile leak. Hepatobiliary scintigraphy and magnetic resonance (MR) cholangiopancreatography with hepatobiliary contrast agents can help detect active or contained bile leaks. MR cholangiopancreatography with hepatobiliary contrast agents has the added advantage of being able to help localize the bile leak, which in turn can help determine if endoscopic management is sufficient or if surgical management is warranted. Endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography may provide diagnostic confirmation and concurrent therapy when nonsurgical management is pursued. A multimodality imaging approach is helpful in diagnosing traumatic or iatrogenic biliary injuries, accurately localizing a bile leak, and determining appropriate treatment.</div><div role="paragraph">©RSNA, 2014</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.343130011">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.343130011">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343130011/asset/images/large/rg.343130011.fig1a.jpeg" height="829" width="528" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span> Internal hemorrhage in a 31-year-old man who was involved in a rollover motor vehicle accident. Arterial phase <b>(a)</b>, portal venous phase <b>(b)</b>, and 5-minute delayed phase <b>(c)</b> CT images demonstrate a focus of hyperattenuating material within the gallbladder lumen. The focus first appears on the portal venous phase image (arrow in <b>b</b>) and persists on the delayed phase image (arrow in <b>c</b>), and as such raises concern for active intraluminal hemorrhage.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343130011&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343130011/asset/images/large/rg.343130011.fig1b.jpeg" height="829" width="499" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span> Internal hemorrhage in a 31-year-old man who was involved in a rollover motor vehicle accident. Arterial phase <b>(a)</b>, portal venous phase <b>(b)</b>, and 5-minute delayed phase <b>(c)</b> CT images demonstrate a focus of hyperattenuating material within the gallbladder lumen. The focus first appears on the portal venous phase image (arrow in <b>b</b>) and persists on the delayed phase image (arrow in <b>c</b>), and as such raises concern for active intraluminal hemorrhage.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343130011&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343130011/asset/images/large/rg.343130011.fig1c.jpeg" height="829" width="523" aria-labelledby="fig1c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1c</span> Internal hemorrhage in a 31-year-old man who was involved in a rollover motor vehicle accident. Arterial phase <b>(a)</b>, portal venous phase <b>(b)</b>, and 5-minute delayed phase <b>(c)</b> CT images demonstrate a focus of hyperattenuating material within the gallbladder lumen. The focus first appears on the portal venous phase image (arrow in <b>b</b>) and persists on the delayed phase image (arrow in <b>c</b>), and as such raises concern for active intraluminal hemorrhage.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343130011&amp;id=fig1c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343130011/asset/images/large/rg.343130011.fig2a.jpeg" height="716" width="950" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span> Gallbladder laceration in a 36-year-old man who sustained a stab wound to the right upper quadrant. <b>(a)</b> CT scan demonstrates a large right rectus sheath hematoma and an AAST grade 3 liver laceration extending to the gallbladder wall (arrow). <b>(b)</b> CT scan demonstrates dependent hyperattenuating material within the gallbladder lumen (arrow), a finding that raises concern for hemorrhage. Laceration of the posterior wall of the gallbladder with intraluminal clot was found at surgery. The patient underwent open cholecystectomy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343130011&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343130011/asset/images/large/rg.343130011.fig2b.jpeg" height="716" width="925" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span> Gallbladder laceration in a 36-year-old man who sustained a stab wound to the right upper quadrant. <b>(a)</b> CT scan demonstrates a large right rectus sheath hematoma and an AAST grade 3 liver laceration extending to the gallbladder wall (arrow). <b>(b)</b> CT scan demonstrates dependent hyperattenuating material within the gallbladder lumen (arrow), a finding that raises concern for hemorrhage. Laceration of the posterior wall of the gallbladder with intraluminal clot was found at surgery. The patient underwent open cholecystectomy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343130011&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343130011/asset/images/large/rg.343130011.fig3a.jpeg" height="886" width="552" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span> Biloma in a 39-year-old man who sustained an AAST grade 4 liver laceration in a motor vehicle accident. <b>(a)</b> Contrast material–enhanced CT image obtained 13 days after the accident demonstrates contrast material from recent ERCP within the gallbladder lumen, with extravasated intraparenchymal contrast material indicative of a focal bile leak (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image obtained 1 week later demonstrates a loculated intrahepatic fluid collection (arrow) in the same location as the bile leak, a finding that is consistent with a biloma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343130011&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343130011/asset/images/large/rg.343130011.fig3b.jpeg" height="886" width="573" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span> Biloma in a 39-year-old man who sustained an AAST grade 4 liver laceration in a motor vehicle accident. <b>(a)</b> Contrast material–enhanced CT image obtained 13 days after the accident demonstrates contrast material from recent ERCP within the gallbladder lumen, with extravasated intraparenchymal contrast material indicative of a focal bile leak (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image obtained 1 week later demonstrates a loculated intrahepatic fluid collection (arrow) in the same location as the bile leak, a finding that is consistent with a biloma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343130011&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343130011/asset/images/large/rg.343130011.fig4a.jpeg" height="682" width="938" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span> Biloma in a 22-year-old man who sustained multiple gunshot wounds. <b>(a)</b> CT scan obtained with intravenous contrast material shows an AAST grade 5 liver laceration (arrow). <b>(b)</b> US image obtained 1 week after admission reveals a subcapsular collection representing a biloma (arrow). The patient subsequently underwent US-guided drainage of the biloma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343130011&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343130011/asset/images/large/rg.343130011.fig4b.jpeg" height="682" width="936" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span> Biloma in a 22-year-old man who sustained multiple gunshot wounds. <b>(a)</b> CT scan obtained with intravenous contrast material shows an AAST grade 5 liver laceration (arrow). <b>(b)</b> US image obtained 1 week after admission reveals a subcapsular collection representing a biloma (arrow). The patient subsequently underwent US-guided drainage of the biloma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343130011&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343130011/asset/images/large/rg.343130011.fig5a.jpeg" height="683" width="938" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span> Intraperitoneal bile leak in a 21-year-old woman who was involved in a motor vehicle accident. <b>(a)</b> CT image obtained at the time of admission demonstrates an AAST grade 3 laceration of the right hepatic lobe (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Hepatobiliary scintigraphic image obtained 3 days later reveals an active intraperitoneal bile leak with radiotracer uptake extending into the right paracolic gutter (straight arrow) and the left upper quadrant (curved arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343130011&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343130011/asset/images/large/rg.343130011.fig5b.jpeg" height="683" width="937" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span> Intraperitoneal bile leak in a 21-year-old woman who was involved in a motor vehicle accident. <b>(a)</b> CT image obtained at the time of admission demonstrates an AAST grade 3 laceration of the right hepatic lobe (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Hepatobiliary scintigraphic image obtained 3 days later reveals an active intraperitoneal bile leak with radiotracer uptake extending into the right paracolic gutter (straight arrow) and the left upper quadrant (curved arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343130011&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343130011/asset/images/large/rg.343130011.fig6a.jpeg" height="674" width="922" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span> Bile leak in a 63-year-old man who sustained multiple injuries when he was trampled by a bull. <b>(a)</b> CT image obtained with intravenous contrast material demonstrates an AAST grade 5 liver laceration (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Hepatobiliary scintigraphic <b>(b)</b> and SPECT/CT <b>(c)</b> images demonstrate the accumulation of bile in the right hepatic dome (straight arrow), with spillage into the right paracolic gutter (curved arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343130011&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343130011/asset/images/large/rg.343130011.fig6b.jpeg" height="674" width="753" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span> Bile leak in a 63-year-old man who sustained multiple injuries when he was trampled by a bull. <b>(a)</b> CT image obtained with intravenous contrast material demonstrates an AAST grade 5 liver laceration (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Hepatobiliary scintigraphic <b>(b)</b> and SPECT/CT <b>(c)</b> images demonstrate the accumulation of bile in the right hepatic dome (straight arrow), with spillage into the right paracolic gutter (curved arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343130011&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343130011/asset/images/large/rg.343130011.fig6c.jpeg" height="876" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig6c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6c</span> Bile leak in a 63-year-old man who sustained multiple injuries when he was trampled by a bull. <b>(a)</b> CT image obtained with intravenous contrast material demonstrates an AAST grade 5 liver laceration (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Hepatobiliary scintigraphic <b>(b)</b> and SPECT/CT <b>(c)</b> images demonstrate the accumulation of bile in the right hepatic dome (straight arrow), with spillage into the right paracolic gutter (curved arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343130011&amp;id=fig6c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343130011/asset/images/large/rg.343130011.fig7.jpeg" height="829" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig7" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7</span> Bile leak in the same patient as in <a href="#fig6a">Figure 6</a>. Axial MR cholangiopancreatographic image obtained with gadoxetate disodium demonstrates active bile leakage from a branch of the proximal right intrahepatic duct (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343130011&amp;id=fig7">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343130011/asset/images/large/rg.343130011.fig8a.jpeg" height="713" width="834" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span> Biloma in a 35-year-old woman who was involved in a motor vehicle accident. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial precontrast T2-weighted <b>(a)</b> and T1-weighted high-resolution isotropic volume examination (THRIVE) <b>(b)</b> MR images demonstrate an AAST grade 2 laceration in the left hepatic lobe (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Postcontrast THRIVE MR image demonstrates the extravasation of gadoxetic acid (arrow), a finding that is indicative of a biloma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343130011&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343130011/asset/images/large/rg.343130011.fig8b.jpeg" height="713" width="841" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span> Biloma in a 35-year-old woman who was involved in a motor vehicle accident. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial precontrast T2-weighted <b>(a)</b> and T1-weighted high-resolution isotropic volume examination (THRIVE) <b>(b)</b> MR images demonstrate an AAST grade 2 laceration in the left hepatic lobe (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Postcontrast THRIVE MR image demonstrates the extravasation of gadoxetic acid (arrow), a finding that is indicative of a biloma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343130011&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343130011/asset/images/large/rg.343130011.fig8c.jpeg" height="727" width="850" aria-labelledby="fig8c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8c</span> Biloma in a 35-year-old woman who was involved in a motor vehicle accident. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial precontrast T2-weighted <b>(a)</b> and T1-weighted high-resolution isotropic volume examination (THRIVE) <b>(b)</b> MR images demonstrate an AAST grade 2 laceration in the left hepatic lobe (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Postcontrast THRIVE MR image demonstrates the extravasation of gadoxetic acid (arrow), a finding that is indicative of a biloma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343130011&amp;id=fig8c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343130011/asset/images/large/rg.343130011.fig9a.jpeg" height="679" width="918" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span> Bilomas in a 43-year-old woman who was an unrestrained passenger and was thrown from a vehicle moving at 70 mph. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image obtained with intravenous contrast material demonstrates an AAST grade 4 liver laceration with active arterial extravasation (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT image obtained 2 weeks later demonstrates a loculated intrahepatic fluid collection (arrow). Bilious fluid was aspirated from this collection, confirming the presence of a biloma. <b>(c)</b> Hepatobiliary scintigraphic image demonstrates a large photopenic defect (straight arrow) corresponding to the known liver laceration, with two contained foci of radiotracer uptake (curved arrows), findings that are suggestive of bilomas. <b>(d)</b> ERCP image shows active extravasation of contrast-enhanced bile from peripheral branches of the right hepatic bile duct. The patient was successfully treated with sphincterotomy and CBD stent placement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343130011&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343130011/asset/images/large/rg.343130011.fig9b.jpeg" height="679" width="757" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span> Bilomas in a 43-year-old woman who was an unrestrained passenger and was thrown from a vehicle moving at 70 mph. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image obtained with intravenous contrast material demonstrates an AAST grade 4 liver laceration with active arterial extravasation (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT image obtained 2 weeks later demonstrates a loculated intrahepatic fluid collection (arrow). Bilious fluid was aspirated from this collection, confirming the presence of a biloma. <b>(c)</b> Hepatobiliary scintigraphic image demonstrates a large photopenic defect (straight arrow) corresponding to the known liver laceration, with two contained foci of radiotracer uptake (curved arrows), findings that are suggestive of bilomas. <b>(d)</b> ERCP image shows active extravasation of contrast-enhanced bile from peripheral branches of the right hepatic bile duct. The patient was successfully treated with sphincterotomy and CBD stent placement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343130011&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343130011/asset/images/large/rg.343130011.fig9c.jpeg" height="744" width="791" aria-labelledby="fig9c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9c</span> Bilomas in a 43-year-old woman who was an unrestrained passenger and was thrown from a vehicle moving at 70 mph. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image obtained with intravenous contrast material demonstrates an AAST grade 4 liver laceration with active arterial extravasation (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT image obtained 2 weeks later demonstrates a loculated intrahepatic fluid collection (arrow). Bilious fluid was aspirated from this collection, confirming the presence of a biloma. <b>(c)</b> Hepatobiliary scintigraphic image demonstrates a large photopenic defect (straight arrow) corresponding to the known liver laceration, with two contained foci of radiotracer uptake (curved arrows), findings that are suggestive of bilomas. <b>(d)</b> ERCP image shows active extravasation of contrast-enhanced bile from peripheral branches of the right hepatic bile duct. The patient was successfully treated with sphincterotomy and CBD stent placement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343130011&amp;id=fig9c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343130011/asset/images/large/rg.343130011.fig9d.jpeg" height="744" width="684" aria-labelledby="fig9d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9d</span> Bilomas in a 43-year-old woman who was an unrestrained passenger and was thrown from a vehicle moving at 70 mph. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image obtained with intravenous contrast material demonstrates an AAST grade 4 liver laceration with active arterial extravasation (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT image obtained 2 weeks later demonstrates a loculated intrahepatic fluid collection (arrow). Bilious fluid was aspirated from this collection, confirming the presence of a biloma. <b>(c)</b> Hepatobiliary scintigraphic image demonstrates a large photopenic defect (straight arrow) corresponding to the known liver laceration, with two contained foci of radiotracer uptake (curved arrows), findings that are suggestive of bilomas. <b>(d)</b> ERCP image shows active extravasation of contrast-enhanced bile from peripheral branches of the right hepatic bile duct. The patient was successfully treated with sphincterotomy and CBD stent placement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343130011&amp;id=fig9d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343130011/asset/images/large/rg.343130011.fig10a.jpeg" height="739" width="870" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span> Bile leak in a 68-year-old man with biliary colic who underwent laparoscopic (converted to open) cholecystectomy secondary to dense adhesions surrounding the gallbladder. <b>(a)</b> Hepatobiliary scintigraphic image obtained the day after surgery demonstrates radiotracer extravasation into the left upper quadrant (arrow). <b>(b)</b> ERCP image helps confirm an active bile leak from a branch of the right hepatic duct (arrow). The patient was successfully treated with sphincterotomy and CBD stent placement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343130011&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343130011/asset/images/large/rg.343130011.fig10b.jpeg" height="739" width="805" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span> Bile leak in a 68-year-old man with biliary colic who underwent laparoscopic (converted to open) cholecystectomy secondary to dense adhesions surrounding the gallbladder. <b>(a)</b> Hepatobiliary scintigraphic image obtained the day after surgery demonstrates radiotracer extravasation into the left upper quadrant (arrow). <b>(b)</b> ERCP image helps confirm an active bile leak from a branch of the right hepatic duct (arrow). The patient was successfully treated with sphincterotomy and CBD stent placement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343130011&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Bala M, Gazalla SA, Faroja M, et al. Complications of high grade liver injuries: management and outcome with focus on bile leaks. <em>Scand J Trauma Resusc Emerg Med</em> 2012;20:20.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1186/1757-7241-20-20">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22444252/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Complications+of+high+grade+liver+injuries%3A+man